Subject: [PATCH 10/42] =?UTF-8?q?inline-3d(#625):=20auto-force=20high-perf?=
 =?UTF-8?q?=20GPU=20adapter=20=E2=80=94=20retire=20--force=5Fhigh=5Fperfor?=
 =?UTF-8?q?mance=5Fgpu?=
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Blocker #5 (dual-GPU cross-adapter NT-handle share). The DisplayXR service
creates the NT-shared keyed-mutex weave input on the runtime's adapter (the
high-performance NVIDIA GPU, per xrGetD3D11GraphicsRequirementsKHR). On a
dual-GPU laptop chrome's GPU process defaulted to the Intel iGPU, so the
service's OpenSharedResource(NT) failed cross-adapter (E_INVALIDARG /
0x80070057). The manual --force_high_performance_gpu launch flag aligned them.

Make it automatic under --enable-inline-3d: the existing DisplayXR block in
ContentBrowserClient::AppendExtraCommandLineSwitches (chrome + content_shell)
now appends the FORCE_HIGH_PERFORMANCE_GPU driver-bug workaround switch to the
gpu-process child command line. This is provably equivalent to the flag — the
underscore --force_high_performance_gpu IS that workaround name, which
gpu_process_host.cc translates the dashed switches::kForceHighPerformanceGPU
into; both converge on FORCE_HIGH_PERFORMANCE_GPU, driving ANGLE EGL_HIGH_POWER
and Dawn HighPerformance adapter selection in the GPU process.

Added //gpu/config to content_shell's is_win deps (chrome/browser already had
it) for gpu::GpuDriverBugWorkaroundTypeToString.

Verified on the Leia box with the flag removed: the GPU weave device's adapter
LUID matched the runtime's (…0001b9d9) and the weave fired
(leia_dp_d3d11_process_atlas weave: vp=(374,920 1810x1054)) with zero
0x80070057. The three --disable-features crutches (TreesInViz, SkiaGraphite)
remain as separate follow-ups.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
